        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3" align="RIGHT"> 
            <p align=LEFT><b><font color="#0c2d83" size="+1" face="Times New Roman, Times, serif">case 
              summaries</font></b> 
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="1"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Administrative 
            Law</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:  
              </b>Licensing action by Board of Examiners of Social Workers (the 
              Board) against state certified social worker for violation of the 
              Occupational Code; Whether circuit court erred in reviewing agency 
              decision for proof of actual harm and in weighing complaining witness’s 
              credibility; MCR 7.105(M); Substantial evidence test; Waiver; Laches; 
              Constitutional rights to marry and procreate; Whether portions of 
              the Occupational Code were unconstitutional due to vagueness; Whether 
              license revocation and fine were an abuse of discretion<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:  
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:  </b>Budde v. Michigan Dep’t of Consumer &amp; Indus. Servs.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:  </b>12323<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Per Curiam – Saad and Smolenski; Concurring in part, Dissenting 
              in part – Hoekstra</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The circuit 
              court applied incorrect legal principles in reversing the Board’s 
              licensing action, revoking petitioner’s state certification and 
              imposing a $5,000 fine, based on lack of actual harm to the complaining 
              witness, a former patient of petitioner’s who alleged a sexual relationship 
              with him. The Occupational Code prohibits a social worker from committing 
              acts of gross negligence and incompetence; the Code does not limit 
              that prohibition to grossly negligent or incompetent acts that result 
              in actual harm to a patient. The court concluded that a certified 
              social worker may violate those provisions of the Code without causing 
              actual harm to a patient, and the circuit court erred as a matter 
              of law when it reviewed the agency’s decision for proof of actual 
              harm to the complaining witness. The circuit court’s order reversing 
              the licensing action was reversed, and the decision and penalty 
              imposed by the Board were reinstated. </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12323.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="2"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Constitutional 
            Law </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Corrections</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b>  
              Deprivation of property without due process; Michigan Department 
              of Corrections (MDOC) former policy of deducting court ordered fees 
              from prisoner accounts in excess of percentage authorized by court 
              order; Prison Litigation Reform Act (PLRA); <i>Hampton v. Hobbs<br>
              </i></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b> U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  Hughes v. Toombs<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:</b>  12311<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Enslen</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Plaintiff-prisoner 
              was granted summary judgment as to defendants’ liability on his 
              claim for deprivation of property without due process arising out 
              of the deduction of 100 percent of the spendable balance in his 
              prisoner account in contravention of court orders requiring smaller 
              deductions. There was no dispute that defendants were state actors, 
              and no serious dispute that plaintiff had a constitutionally protected 
              property interest in the money in his prison account at the time 
              of its taking. Defendants were authorized by court order to take 
              a portion of that money for filing fees for an action plaintiff 
              brought in federal district court. However, the money taken exceeded 
              the percentage allowed by the PLRA and the court order, and defendants 
              were aware of this when they effected the taking. This action was 
              taken pursuant to an established MDOC procedure, and no procedural 
              due process of any kind was afforded to plaintiff prior to the taking. 
              </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/080801/12311.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="3"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Consumer 
            Rights</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Contracts</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b> 
              Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO); Voluntary-payment 
              doctrine; Breach of contract; Michigan Consumer Protection Act; 
              Unjust enrichment<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Eastern District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Durant v. Servicemaster Co.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:</b> 12336<b> <br>
              </b></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Gadola</font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Defendants’ 
              motion to dismiss plaintiffs’ RICO claim was granted because plaintiffs 
              failed to adequately plead the existence of a distinct enterprise. 
              Plaintiffs, lawn care customers of defendant, alleged that defendants 
              wrongly added a “fuel surcharge” to their bills. Defendants’ motion 
              to dismiss in all other respects was denied. </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/090501/12336.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
