        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Constitutional Law</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b>  
              Deprivation of property without due process; Michigan Department 
              of Corrections (MDOC) former policy of deducting court ordered fees 
              from prisoner accounts in excess of percentage authorized by court 
              order; Prison Litigation Reform Act (PLRA); <i>Hampton v. Hobbs<br>
              </i></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b> U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  Hughes v. Toombs<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:</b>  12311<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Enslen</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Plaintiff-prisoner 
              was granted summary judgment as to defendants’ liability on his 
              claim for deprivation of property without due process arising out 
              of the deduction of 100 percent of the spendable balance in his 
              prisoner account in contravention of court orders requiring smaller 
              deductions. There was no dispute that defendants were state actors, 
              and no serious dispute that plaintiff had a constitutionally protected 
              property interest in the money in his prison account at the time 
              of its taking. Defendants were authorized by court order to take 
              a portion of that money for filing fees for an action plaintiff 
              brought in federal district court. However, the money taken exceeded 
              the percentage allowed by the PLRA and the court order, and defendants 
              were aware of this when they effected the taking. This action was 
              taken pursuant to an established MDOC procedure, and no procedural 
              due process of any kind was afforded to plaintiff prior to the taking. 
              </font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/080801/12311.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
