        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="6"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Criminal 
            Law </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Opinion testimony by police officer that another suspect was 
              not involved in the crime; Denial of defendant's right to put on 
              a viable defense<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Supreme Court<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>People v. Jordan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12333<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Corrigan, Cavanagh, Weaver, Kelly, Taylor, Young, Jr., and Markman</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">In an order, 
              the court reversed the judgment of the Court of Appeals reversing 
              defendant's conviction and remanding for a new trial (see <b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/051101/10197.pdf">e-Journal 
              #10197 </a></b>in the 5/16/01 edition) and remanded the case to 
              the Court of Appeals for consideration of issues raised but not 
              addressed in its decision. Witnesses whom the police officer relied 
              on to find noninvolvement by another suspect, appeared and testified 
              at trial that the other suspect was upstairs when the shot was fired 
              in the basement, killing the victim. The record indicated no objection 
              was raised to the officer's testimony and the challenge raised on 
              appeal was not preserved. The outcome of the trial would not have 
              changed if the officer had failed to explain why his investigation 
              led him not to focus on the other suspect. </font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/supreme/2001/091101/12333.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b> 
              <i>Habeas corpus</i>; The Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty 
              Act; The one-year grace period; Equitable tolling<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Morris v. Berghuis<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12339<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>McKeague</font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Petitioner’s 
              application for <i>habeas corpus</i> was dismissed without prejudice 
              because it was barred by the one-year statute of limitation under 
              § 2244(d). Petitioner contended that he had not been convicted and 
              sentenced and that he was unlawfully incarcerated, but did not explain 
              why he waited so many years to bring either of his <i>habeas</i> 
              actions. The court could not understand why someone who was wrongfully 
              incarcerated for mistaken identity would have waited more than 10 
              years before raising the issue. Petitioner’s certificate of appealability 
              was denied because he failed to make a substantial showing of the 
              denial of a constitutional right.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/083101/12339.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Prosecutorial misconduct; Denial of request to disqualify juror; 
              Proportionality of sentence<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>People v. Blackmon<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12318<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam - Hoekstra, Talbot, and Kelly</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Although there 
              were instances of prosecutorial misconduct in the form of evidence 
              of gang affiliation and impeachment of a prosecution witness that 
              were prejudicial and merited exclusion under MRE 403, reversal was 
              not required because the untainted evidence against defendant was 
              overwhelming. The case arose from a shooting incident, which resulted 
              in the death of a bystander and injury to two other bystanders. 
              Throughout the proceedings, the prosecution advanced a theory that 
              the shooting was related to gang activity. The eyewitness testimony 
              alone would support a conviction of the crimes charged where two 
              eyewitnesses testified that they saw defendant shooting. Defendant's 
              convictions of second-degree murder, two counts of assault with 
              intent to do great bodily harm, and felony firearm were affirmed. 
              </font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12318.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="7"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Driver's 
            License Reinstatement</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Whether the trial court erred in considering evidence that was 
              not presented to the hearing officer; Whether the hearing officer's 
              decision was supported by competent, material, and substantial evidence; 
              Whether the hearing officer's decision was arbitrary, capricious, 
              and an unwarranted exercise of discretion; Driver's License Appeal 
              Division (DLAD); <i>Roman v. Secretary of State<br>
              </i></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Barden v. Secretary of State<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12324<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam - Jansen, Collins, and Cooper</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trial court 
              erred at a matter of law in determining that its review was not 
              limited to the administrative record compiled before the DLAD hearing 
              officer and in considering evidence beyond both the hearing record 
              and the driving record. Under § 323(6) the trial court<i> shall 
              </i>confine its consideration of the DLAD's determination to a review 
              of the administrative record. Under the clear and unambiguous terms 
              of the statute, the trial court could not consider evidence that 
              was not presented to the hearing officer. The trial court also erred 
              in finding that the hearing officer's decision was not supported 
              by competent, material, and substantial evidence on the whole record 
              and that the decision was arbitrary, capricious, and an unwarranted 
              abuse of discretion. Reversed and remanded for reinstatement of 
              the administrative decision denying the petition for reinstatement 
              of plaintiff's drivers license.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12324.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="8"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Employment 
            &amp; Labor Law </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Negligence &amp; Intentional Tort</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Negligence of an independent contractor; Whether defendant owed 
              a duty of care to plaintiff; Doctrines of “retained control” and 
              “inherently dangerous activity”; Whether defendant was barred from 
              asserting the affirmative defense that an independent contractor 
              performed the carpet installation<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:</b>  
              Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  Williams v. Master Craft Carpet Serv., Inc.         <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12319<b>  <br>
              </b></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Per Curiam – Doctoroff, Saad, and Wilder</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Neither the 
              “retained control” exception nor the “inherently dangerous activity” 
              exception applied, therefore, defendant could not be held directly 
              or vicariously liable to plaintiff for the alleged negligence of 
              an independent contractor. Plaintiff slipped and fell on fresh glue 
              recently applied to the floor. Defendant could not be held directly 
              liable for plaintiff’s injuries under the doctrine of retained control 
              because defendant had no duty to implement safety standards and 
              precautions in the work area to protect multiple subcontractors 
              since there was no evidence multiple subcontractors worked or were 
              expected to work at the site. The installation of carpet does not 
              constitute an inherently dangerous activity, but instead is a routine 
              task carrying only a minimal, ordinary risk. The trial court properly 
              granted defendant’s motion for summary disposition. Affirmed.<b>  
              </b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12319.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="9"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Family 
            Law</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Divorce; The 1996 judgment; MCR 2.507(H); MCR 3.211(B); Arbitration; 
              Merger; Fault; Cash withdrawals; Household expenses; Judgment interest<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Shatzman v. Shatzman<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12327<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam - Fitzgerald and Markey; Concurring in result only 
              - Gage</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trial court 
              erred in incorporating into its judgment a settlement and a schedule 
              of assets, their values, and their distributions to which defendant 
              had not agreed, and the 1996 judgment did not fully determine the 
              parties' property rights as required by court rule. Because it reserved 
              for further determination the final adjudication of certain property 
              issues, the 1996 judgment should not have been entered and should 
              not have been treated as a final judgment with respect to those 
              pending issues. Defendant was prejudiced from having what was not 
              truly a final judgment treated as a limitation on his ability to 
              litigate further those issues unresolved by the judgment. Therefore, 
              reversal was required on any issues that were not properly subject 
              to or which were not contemplated by arbitration. Affirmed in part, 
              reversed in part, and remanded for further proceedings. </font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12327.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="10"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Intellectual 
            Property </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Patent infringement; Reverse prosecution history estoppel<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>American Seating Co. v. Transportation Seating, Inc.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12338<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Enslen</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The court held 
              that defendant's product did not literally infringement on plaintiff's 
              patent for a wheelchair restraint system for use in vehicles because 
              the moveable slide arm in defendant's product was not &quot;locked&quot; 
              to the vehicle at a further location to later secure a wheelchair, 
              as required by plaintiff's patent. Plaintiff's patent included a 
              specification of a locking mechanism used to lock the moveable element 
              to the vehicle in the operational position. Defendant's product 
              required the presence of a wheelchair before the movable slide arm 
              is held to the guide element in place by friction between these 
              two components. Therefore, because the movable slide arm in defendant's 
              product could not be held in place without the presence of a wheelchair, 
              the movable slide arm was not locked to the vehicle in order to 
              subsequently secure the wheelchair, and did not infringe on plaintiff's 
              patent. The court granted defendant summary judgment on this issue.  
              </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/080801/12338.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Litigation</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Trademark infringement; Unfair competition<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Review Directories Inc. v. McLeodUSA Publishing Co.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12331<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Enslen</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The court denied 
              plaintiff's motion for summary judgment on its claims of federal 
              and common law trademark infringement and unfair competition because 
              in a previous opinion denying defendant's motion for summary judgment, 
              the court held that a rational trier of fact could find the marks 
              either descriptive or distinctive and the issue had to be determined 
              by the jury. The court concluded that the issue had to be determined 
              before it can be decided whether defendant infringed on plaintiff's 
              marks because if the marks are determined generic, they can never 
              be protected trademarks. Further, if the marks are determined to 
              be descriptive, plaintiff must prove that they have secondary meaning 
              before they can be protected under trademark law. Until these questions 
              of fact are determined by the jury, the ultimate question of infringement 
              cannot be decided. </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/080601/12331.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><a name="11"></a><b>Litigation</b></font></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Intellectual Property</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Trademark infringement; Unfair competition<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Review Directories Inc. v. McLeodUSA Publishing Co.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12331<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Enslen</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The court denied 
              plaintiff's motion for summary judgment on its claims of federal 
              and common law trademark infringement and unfair competition because 
              in a previous opinion denying defendant's motion for summary judgment, 
              the court held that a rational trier of fact could find the marks 
              either descriptive or distinctive and the issue had to be determined 
              by the jury. The court concluded that the issue had to be determined 
              before it can be decided whether defendant infringed on plaintiff's 
              marks because if the marks are determined generic, they can never 
              be protected trademarks. Further, if the marks are determined to 
              be descriptive, plaintiff must prove that they have secondary meaning 
              before they can be protected under trademark law. Until these questions 
              of fact are determined by the jury, the ultimate question of infringement 
              cannot be decided. </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/080601/12331.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="12"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Negligence 
            &amp; Intentional Tort</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:  
              </b>Employee provision of the governmental immunity act (MCL 691.1407(2)); 
              <i>Dedes v. South Lyon Community Sch.</i>; <i>Robinson v. Detroit</i> 
              and <i>Cooper v. Wade<br>
              </i></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:  
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:  </b>Daniels v. Peterson<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:  </b>12317<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Per Curiam – Saad, Zahra, and Collins</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Defendants 
              were entitled to summary disposition because plaintiffs’ allegation 
              that defendants were merely <i>a </i>proximate cause of their injuries 
              was insufficient as a matter of law to overcome defendants’ governmental 
              immunity. Plaintiffs’ first amended complaint alleged that “as a 
              direct and proximate result of the gross negligence and deliberate 
              indifference” of the defendants’ joint or individual conduct, “the 
              defendants proximately caused” the injuries suffered by one of the 
              plaintiffs when a train struck his semi-truck. That allegation plainly 
              did not allege that defendants’ conduct was <i>the</i> proximate 
              cause of plaintiffs’ injuries. Granting defendants’ motion for rehearing 
              from its earlier decision (see <b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/040601/9887.pdf">e-Journal 
              # 9887</a></b>, in the 4/12/01 edition) remanding the case to the 
              trial court, the court vacated that decision and affirmed summary 
              disposition for defendants.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12317.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:  
              </b>Governmental immunity; Highway exception to governmental immunity; 
              Whether the trailway was a “sidewalk”; Failure to warn as opposed 
              to failure to maintain and repair; Public duty doctrine; Gross negligence; 
              Exception to governmental immunity based on nuisance <i>per se </i> <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:</b>  
              Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b> Palmer v. Charter Twp. of Orion          <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:  </b>12322<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):   
              </b>Per Curiam – Doctoroff, Murphy, and Zahra</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trial court 
              properly determined that plaintiff’s claim did not fall within the 
              highway exception to governmental immunity and granted summary disposition 
              to the township on the basis of governmental immunity. The court 
              concluded that the trailway where plaintiff was riding her bicycle 
              and hit a depression that had been caused by erosion, was not a 
              “sidewalk” for purposes of government immunity, but a surface used 
              for public recreational purposes. The fact that part of the trailway 
              ran close to a highway did not make it a “sidewalk”. Plaintiff’s 
              argument that she alleged a failure to warn claim, as opposed to 
              a claim for failure to maintain and repair, did not alter the court’s 
              conclusion. Affirmed. <b> </b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12322.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Contracts</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:  
              </b>Negligence and breach of warranty claims in connection with 
              recommended feed change in deer farming operation; Sufficient evidence 
              of causation to submit issue to jury; Exclusion of plaintiff’s tax 
              records and evidence that an elk herd receiving same feed did not 
              have a problem; Jury instruction that plaintiff had no obligation 
              to obtain an autopsy of deer<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:  
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:  </b>Whitetail Enters. v. West Branch Farmers Coop., Inc.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:  </b>12326<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Per Curiam – Neff, Sawyer, and Fitzgerald</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Plaintiff-deer 
              farming operation presented sufficient evidence of causation in 
              connection with losses arising from a recommended feed change to 
              warrant submitting the issue to the jury. Plaintiff began adding 
              a salt product to the deer feed in accordance with a recipe recommended 
              by a nutritionist from one of defendants. Several adult deer subsequently 
              died, and a year’s fawn crop was lost. Both the attending veterinarian 
              and plaintiff’s expert testified to a high likelihood of salt poisoning 
              and only a very low likelihood of some other cause. The problem 
              started about two weeks after the salt was introduced and resolved 
              shortly after it was removed. Further, there was a similar problem 
              with another herd that was fed the salt, and no problem with a third 
              herd that was not. At a minimum, it was reasonable for the jury 
              to conclude that plaintiff established the cause of death was excess 
              salt in the feed. Judgment for plaintiff was affirmed.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12326.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Employment &amp; Labor Law  </b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Negligence of an independent contractor; Whether defendant owed 
              a duty of care to plaintiff; Doctrines of “retained control” and 
              “inherently dangerous activity”; Whether defendant was barred from 
              asserting the affirmative defense that an independent contractor 
              performed the carpet installation<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:</b>  
              Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  Williams v. Master Craft Carpet Serv., Inc.         <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12319<b>  <br>
              </b></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Per Curiam – Doctoroff, Saad, and Wilder</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Neither the 
              “retained control” exception nor the “inherently dangerous activity” 
              exception applied, therefore, defendant could not be held directly 
              or vicariously liable to plaintiff for the alleged negligence of 
              an independent contractor. Plaintiff slipped and fell on fresh glue 
              recently applied to the floor. Defendant could not be held directly 
              liable for plaintiff’s injuries under the doctrine of retained control 
              because defendant had no duty to implement safety standards and 
              precautions in the work area to protect multiple subcontractors 
              since there was no evidence multiple subcontractors worked or were 
              expected to work at the site. The installation of carpet does not 
              constitute an inherently dangerous activity, but instead is a routine 
              task carrying only a minimal, ordinary risk. The trial court properly 
              granted defendant’s motion for summary disposition. Affirmed.<b>  
              </b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12319.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80"><a name="13"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Tax</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="TOP"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:  
              </b>Use tax assessment; Whether an out-of-state mobile and modular 
              home manufacturer had a substantial nexus with Michigan to warrant 
              imposition of use tax; § 4(b) exemption and the Commerce Clause 
              of the U.S. Constitution; <i>Quill Corp. v. North Dakota</i>; <i>Magnetek 
              Controls, Inc. v. Department of Treasury<br>
              </i></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:  
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Unpublished)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:  </b>Hi-Tech Hous., Inc. v. Department of Treasury<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:  </b>12320<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Per Curiam – Neff, Sawyer, and Fitzgerald</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Petitioner, 
              an Indiana-based mobile and modular home manufacturer, had a substantial 
              nexus with Michigan that permitted respondent, consistent with the 
              Commerce Clause, to impose the obligation on petitioner to collect 
              use tax on its sales to Michigan customers. Evidence was submitted 
              from which the Tax Tribunal could reasonably infer that petitioner’s 
              written warranty obligated it to make structural repairs at the 
              customer’s site if defects were discovered within the first year 
              after purchase. Petitioner would reimburse its customers for any 
              warranty repairs the customer made, or would hire independent contractors 
              to make warranty repairs if the customer was unable to do so. If 
              necessary, petitioner would send a representative to Michigan to 
              assess the situation, and the representative occasionally made the 
              repair or contacted a local contractor to make the repair. Petitioner 
              had “more than a slightest presence” in Michigan. Affirmed.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/091401/12320.pdf">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
